<h2><a name=3D"Make_a_backup"></a>Backup all your data before upgrade from =
Ubuntu 20.04 (Focal Fossa) to Ubuntu 22.04 (Jammy Jellyfish) <a href=3D"htt=
ps://www.cyberciti.biz/faq/upgrade-ubuntu-20-04-lts-to-22-04-lts/#TOC" titl=
e=3D"Jump back to the table of contents (TOC)" style=3D"text-decoration:non=
e;=20
	font-size: 40px;
margin-left: 7px;
font-weight: bolder;">=E2=86=91</a></h2>
<ul>
<li>Make sure you <strong>keep all verified backups of important files and =
databases</strong>. Most cloud server providers like Linode or AWS have an =
option to make snapshots. So take advantage of such service.</li>
<li>Also, make sure you have free disk space. For example, I always ensure =
that I have <strong>at least 30GB of free disk space</strong> on my VM. Use=
 the <a href=3D"https://www.cyberciti.biz/faq/df-command-examples-in-linux-=
unix/" title=3D"How to use df command in Linux / Unix {with examples}">df c=
ommand</a>:<br>
<code><span title=3D"The shell prompt usually ends in a $ sign and is not p=
art of the command for the nonprivileged user." class=3D"normaluserprompt">=
$ </span>df -H</code>
  </li>
<li>The upgrade process takes its sweet time due to the speed of the intern=
et and other factors. <strong>Please do not cancel the operation once start=
ed</strong>, as it will leave your Ubuntu machine in an inconsistent state.=
 </li>
<li>Ensure you are <strong>running the server on UPS or your laptop battery=
 is fully charged</strong>.</li>
<li>To avoid data loss on your desktop, close all apps, including browser w=
indows. For example, I closed my Firefox on Ubuntu Linux 20.04 LTS desktop.=
</li>
<li>All <strong>third party mirrors and repositories are commented out duri=
ng the upgrade process, making them disabled</strong>. For example, Google =
Chrome repo and others will get disabled. You need to enable them after the=
 upgrade procedure is completed. You can find 3rd party repos or mirros in =
the <tt>/etc/apt/sources.list.d/</tt> directory.</li>
<li>I tested instructions on Ubuntu Linux 20.04 LTS server and desktop.</li=
>
</ul>
<h2><a name=3D"What's_new_in_Ubuntu_22.04?"></a>What=E2=80=99s new in Ubunt=
u 22.04 LTS? <a href=3D"https://www.cyberciti.biz/faq/upgrade-ubuntu-20-04-=
lts-to-22-04-lts/#TOC" title=3D"Jump back to the table of contents (TOC)" s=
tyle=3D"text-decoration:none;=20
	font-size: 40px;
margin-left: 7px;
font-weight: bolder;">=E2=86=91</a></h2>
<p>New features and apps that care about most:</p>
<ul>
<li>Apache 2.4.52</li>
<li>BIND 9.18</li>
<li>Corosync 3.16</li>
<li>Django 3.2.12</li>
<li>Firefox 99 (Firefox is now only provided in Ubuntu as a snap)</li>
<li>GNOME has been updated to include new features and fixes from GNOME 41 =
and GNOME 42</li>
<li>LibreOffice 7.3 </li>
<li>Linux kernel v5.15.0-25</li>
<li>MySQL  8.0.28</li>
<li>NetworkManager 1.36</li>
<li>nftables is default as backend for the firewall</li>
<li>Pacemaker 2.1.2</li>
<li>Perl v5.34.0</li>
<li>PHP  8.1.2</li>
<li>PostgreSQL 14.2</li>
<li>Python 3.10.4</li>
<li>Ruby 3.0</li>
<li>Samba 4.15.5</li>
<li>ssh-rsa is now disabled by default in OpenSSH.</li>
<li>Thunderbird 91</li>
</ul>
<h2>Upgrading from Ubuntu 20.04 LTS to 22.04 LTS <a href=3D"https://www.cyb=
erciti.biz/faq/upgrade-ubuntu-20-04-lts-to-22-04-lts/#TOC" title=3D"Jump ba=
ck to the table of contents (TOC)" style=3D"text-decoration:none;=20
	font-size: 40px;
margin-left: 7px;
font-weight: bolder;">=E2=86=91</a></h2>
<div class=3D"extend  ">
<div class=3D"alert"><strong><span style=3D"color: rgb(255, 0, 0);">WARNING=
!</span></strong> Make a backup. Do not proceed further without backups. Th=
e nixCraft is not liable for failed upgrade procedures and data loss.</div>
</div>
<h3>Check /etc/update-manager/release-upgrades file (needed for both GUI an=
d CLI methods)</h3>
<p>Check for default behavior for the release upgrader by using the <a href=
=3D"https://www.cyberciti.biz/faq/linux-unix-appleosx-bsd-cat-command-examp=
les/" title=3D"cat Command in Linux / Unix with examples">cat</a>/<a href=
=3D"https://bash.cyberciti.biz/guide/More_command" title=3D"More command - =
Linux Bash Shell Scripting Tutorial Wiki">more</a> or <a href=3D"https://ba=
sh.cyberciti.biz/guide/Less_command" title=3D"Less command - Linux Bash She=
ll Scripting Tutorial Wiki">less command</a>:<br>
<code><span title=3D"The shell prompt usually ends in a $ sign and is not p=
art of the command for the nonprivileged user." class=3D"normaluserprompt">=
$ </span>less /etc/update-manager/release-upgrades</code><br>
And make sure the following line is set to lts:</p>


<div class=3D"wp-geshi-highlight-wrap5"><div class=3D"wp-geshi-highlight-wr=
ap4"><div class=3D"wp-geshi-highlight-wrap3"><div class=3D"wp-geshi-highlig=
ht-wrap2"><div class=3D"wp-geshi-highlight-wrap"><div class=3D"wp-geshi-hig=
hlight"><div class=3D"ini"><pre class=3D"de1"><span class=3D"re1">Prompt</s=
pan><span class=3D"sy0">=3D</span><span class=3D"re2">lts</span></pre></div=
></div></div></div></div></div></div>


<p>The procedure is as follows to upgrade Ubuntu 20.04 to 22.04.</p>
<h3><a name=3D"Update_your_system"></a>Step 1 =E2=80=93 Update your system =
<a href=3D"https://www.cyberciti.biz/faq/upgrade-ubuntu-20-04-lts-to-22-04-=
lts/#TOC" title=3D"Jump back to the table of contents (TOC)" style=3D"text-=
decoration:none;=20
	font-size: 40px;
margin-left: 7px;
font-weight: bolder;">=E2=86=91</a></h3>
<p>Open the terminal application. For remote server log in using the ssh co=
mmand. First, find all packages that are on hold, type the apt-mark command=
:<br>
<code><span title=3D"The shell prompt usually ends in a $ sign and is not p=
art of the command for the nonprivileged user." class=3D"normaluserprompt">=
$ </span>sudo apt-mark showhold</code><br>
If you see an empty output, there are no held back packages, and you can pr=
oceed safely. Otherwise, you need to remove a hold on packages using the ap=
t-mark command. For instance, unhold the packages as follows (replace pkg1 =
pkg2 with actual names):<br>
<code><span title=3D"The shell prompt usually ends in a $ sign and is not p=
art of the command for the nonprivileged user." class=3D"normaluserprompt">=
$ </span>sudo apt-mark unhold pkg1 pkg2</code><br>
Next, update current system using the <a href=3D"https://www.cyberciti.biz/=
faq/ubuntu-lts-debian-linux-apt-command-examples/" title=3D"apt Command Exa=
mples for Ubuntu/Debian Linux">apt command</a>:<br>
<code><span title=3D"The shell prompt usually ends in a $ sign and is not p=
art of the command for the nonprivileged user." class=3D"normaluserprompt">=
$ </span>sudo apt update <span style=3D"color: #999999;">#&lt;--Refresh the=
 apt repo</span><br>
<span title=3D"The shell prompt usually ends in a $ sign and is not part of=
 the command for the nonprivileged user." class=3D"normaluserprompt">$ </sp=
an>sudo apt upgrade <span style=3D"color: #999999;">#&lt;--Now apply all up=
grades</span></code><br>
</p><div id=3D"attachment_150378" style=3D"width: 609px" class=3D"wp-captio=
n aligncenter"><img decoding=3D"async" aria-describedby=3D"caption-attachme=
nt-150378" src=3D"https://www.cyberciti.biz/media/new/faq/2022/04/How-to-ug=
prade-and-patch-Ubuntu-20.04-LTS-599x443.png" alt=3D"How to ugprade and pat=
ch Ubuntu 20.04 LTS" width=3D"599" height=3D"443" class=3D"size-medium wp-i=
mage-150378"><p id=3D"caption-attachment-150378" class=3D"wp-caption-text">=
Patching Ubuntu 20.04 LTS</p></div>
<a href=3D"https://www.cyberciti.biz/faq/howto-reboot-linux/" title=3D"Rebo=
ot Linux System Command">Reboot the Ubuntu Linux box</a> if a new Linux ker=
nel is installed on the system using the <a href=3D"https://www.cyberciti.b=
iz/faq/howto-shutdown-linux/" title=3D"How To Shutdown Linux Using Command =
Line">shutdown command</a> or <a href=3D"https://www.cyberciti.biz/faq/howt=
o-reboot-linux/" title=3D"Reboot Linux System Command">reboot command</a>:<=
br>
<code><span title=3D"The shell prompt usually ends in a $ sign and is not p=
art of the command for the nonprivileged user." class=3D"normaluserprompt">=
$ </span>sudo reboot</code><p></p>
<h3><a name=3D"Finding_the_current_kernel_version"></a>Step 2 =E2=80=93 Not=
e down the <a href=3D"https://www.cyberciti.biz/faq/find-linux-distribution=
-name-version-number/" title=3D"How To Find Out My Linux Distribution Name =
and Version">current Linux distro name and kernel version</a> <a href=3D"ht=
tps://www.cyberciti.biz/faq/upgrade-ubuntu-20-04-lts-to-22-04-lts/#TOC" tit=
le=3D"Jump back to the table of contents (TOC)" style=3D"text-decoration:no=
ne;=20
	font-size: 40px;
margin-left: 7px;
font-weight: bolder;">=E2=86=91</a></h3>
<p>Use the uname command and lsb_release command as follows:<br>
<code><span title=3D"The shell prompt usually ends in a $ sign and is not p=
art of the command for the nonprivileged user." class=3D"normaluserprompt">=
$ </span>uname -mrs<br>
<span title=3D"The shell prompt usually ends in a $ sign and is not part of=
 the command for the nonprivileged user." class=3D"normaluserprompt">$ </sp=
an>lsb_release -a</code><br>
</p><div id=3D"attachment_150379" style=3D"width: 587px" class=3D"wp-captio=
n aligncenter"><img loading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" aria-describedby=3D=
"caption-attachment-150379" src=3D"https://www.cyberciti.biz/media/new/faq/=
2022/04/Note-down-Ubuntu-Linux-20.04-LTS-kernel-version-command.png" alt=3D=
"Note down Ubuntu Linux 20.04 LTS kernel version command" width=3D"577" hei=
ght=3D"353" class=3D"size-full wp-image-150379"><p id=3D"caption-attachment=
-150379" class=3D"wp-caption-text">Finding out Ubuntu Linux kernel version<=
/p></div>
<h3><a name=3D"Open_TCP_port_1022"></a>Step 3 =E2=80=93 Open TCP port 1022 =
<a href=3D"https://www.cyberciti.biz/faq/upgrade-ubuntu-20-04-lts-to-22-04-=
lts/#TOC" title=3D"Jump back to the table of contents (TOC)" style=3D"text-=
decoration:none;=20
	font-size: 40px;
margin-left: 7px;
font-weight: bolder;">=E2=86=91</a></h3>
<p>Are you typing the following commands over ssh based session? Then, plea=
se open an additional <a href=3D"https://www.cyberciti.biz/faq/ufw-allow-in=
coming-ssh-connections-from-a-specific-ip-address-subnet-on-ubuntu-debian/"=
 title=3D"How to open ssh 22/TCP port using ufw on Ubuntu/Debian Linux">ssh=
 port using ufw command</a> which will be started at port 1022. For example=
:<br>
<code><span title=3D"The shell prompt usually ends in a $ sign and is not p=
art of the command for the nonprivileged user." class=3D"normaluserprompt">=
$ </span>sudo ufw allow 1022/tcp comment 'Open port ssh tcp port 1022 as fa=
ilsafe option for upgrades'</code><br>
Verify it:<br>
<code><span title=3D"The shell prompt usually ends in a $ sign and is not p=
art of the command for the nonprivileged user." class=3D"normaluserprompt">=
$ </span>sudo ufw status</code><br>
<span style=3D"color: #999999;">Sample rules:</span></p>


<div class=3D"wp-geshi-highlight-wrap5"><div class=3D"wp-geshi-highlight-wr=
ap4"><div class=3D"wp-geshi-highlight-wrap3"><div class=3D"wp-geshi-highlig=
ht-wrap2"><div class=3D"wp-geshi-highlight-wrap"><div class=3D"wp-geshi-hig=
hlight"><div class=3D"ini"><pre class=3D"de1">Status: active
&nbsp;
To                         Action      From
--                         ------      ----
