<p>Then run the <a href=3D"https://www.cyberciti.biz/faq/ubuntu-lts-debian-=
linux-apt-command-examples/" title=3D"apt Command Examples for Ubuntu/Debia=
n Linux">apt command</a>:<br>
<code><span title=3D"The shell prompt usually ends in a $ sign and is not p=
art of the command for the nonprivileged user." class=3D"normaluserprompt">=
$ </span>sudo apt update<br>
<span title=3D"The shell prompt usually ends in a $ sign and is not part of=
 the command for the nonprivileged user." class=3D"normaluserprompt">$ </sp=
an>sudo apt upgrade</code><br>
Finally, clean up unwanted and unused leftover packages:<br>
<code><span title=3D"The shell prompt usually ends in a $ sign and is not p=
art of the command for the nonprivileged user." class=3D"normaluserprompt">=
$ </span>sudo apt autoremove --purge</code></p>
<h2><a name=3D"Upgrade_to_22.04_using_GUI"></a>How to upgrade to 22.04 LTS =
from 20.04 LTS using a GUI method <a href=3D"https://www.cyberciti.biz/faq/=
upgrade-ubuntu-20-04-lts-to-22-04-lts/#TOC" title=3D"Jump back to the table=
 of contents (TOC)" style=3D"text-decoration:none;=20
	font-size: 40px;
margin-left: 7px;
font-weight: bolder;">=E2=86=91</a></h2>
<p>Make sure you apply all updates before typing the following commands. In=
 other words:<br>
<code><span title=3D"The shell prompt usually ends in a $ sign and is not p=
art of the command for the nonprivileged user." class=3D"normaluserprompt">=
$ </span>sudo apt update<br>
<span title=3D"The shell prompt usually ends in a $ sign and is not part of=
 the command for the nonprivileged user." class=3D"normaluserprompt">$ </sp=
an>sudo apt upgrade<br>
<span title=3D"The shell prompt usually ends in a $ sign and is not part of=
 the command for the nonprivileged user." class=3D"normaluserprompt">$ </sp=
an>sudo reboot <small><span style=3D"color: rgb(255, 0, 0);"># &lt;-- if a =
new kernel installed</span></small></code><br>
Type the following command to start GUI update wizard: </p>
<div class=3D"note">If you do not get updates, try to pass the <kbd>-d</kbd=
>. If using the latest supported release, upgrade to the development releas=
e. For example:<br>
<code><span title=3D"The shell prompt usually ends in a $ sign and is not p=
art of the command for the nonprivileged user." class=3D"normaluserprompt">=
$ </span>sudo do-release-upgrade -f DistUpgradeViewGtk3 -d</code><br>
OR<br>
<code><span title=3D"The shell prompt usually ends in a $ sign and is not p=
art of the command for the nonprivileged user." class=3D"normaluserprompt">=
$ </span>sudo update-manager -c -d</code>
</div>
<p><code><span title=3D"The shell prompt usually ends in a $ sign and is no=
t part of the command for the nonprivileged user." class=3D"normaluserpromp=
t">$ </span>sudo do-release-upgrade -f DistUpgradeViewGtk3</code><br>
OR use the following command:<br>
<code><span title=3D"The shell prompt usually ends in a $ sign and is not p=
art of the command for the nonprivileged user." class=3D"normaluserprompt">=
$ </span>sudo update-manager -c</code><br>
</p><div id=3D"attachment_150390" style=3D"width: 609px" class=3D"wp-captio=
n aligncenter"><a href=3D"https://www.cyberciti.biz/media/new/faq/2022/04/G=
UI-Update-1.png"><img loading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" aria-describedby=
=3D"caption-attachment-150390" src=3D"https://www.cyberciti.biz/media/new/f=
